{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: the failure is at module handoff (collectors -> aggregation payload -> summary step), not a single pure function. REAL-INFRA: no real OS/network is required if source clients are stubbed. LLM-DEP: this checks payload completeness before model output quality. CANDIDATE-TEST-CHECK: (Integration) run orchestrator with three stub source adapters returning distinct markers; assert summary-generator input contains all three markers; catches dropped/miswired source data. (Unit alternative) test only payload builder with preconstructed inputs; catches merge bugs but misses fetch-orchestration omission. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected because behavior text is about \"content passed\" not real HTTP/email delivery; Agentic rejected because no claim about summary quality/model judgment.","test_description":"Integration test with stub metrics/issue/deploy clients and a spy summary generator; execute one report run and assert the generator receives fields from all three sources in one payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"A lower-level unit test would not reliably catch orchestration omissions between source retrieval modules and the summary handoff.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: resilience behavior appears when source adapter errors propagate through orchestration and rendering. REAL-INFRA: a stubbed adapter exception can reproduce the unavailability path; real network outage is not required to verify fallback logic. MOCK-HIDE: full mocking does not necessarily hide this specific failure if the error is injected at module boundary. CANDIDATE-TEST-CHECK: (Integration) one source stub raises timeout/error, others return data; assert report output includes \"data unavailable\" for failing section and process completes; catches abort-on-first-failure regressions. (Unit alternative) test only formatter inserts fallback label; misses orchestration abort behavior. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected because behavior text does not require real transport semantics, only graceful degradation.","test_description":"Integration test wiring orchestrator + renderer with one failing source client stub; assert non-failing sections are present and failing section is replaced by `data unavailable` without raising fatal error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Chosen test requires cross-module error handling and rendering, which is above Unit but below System.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: correctness depends on what the summary generator actually writes (content fidelity), which is model-output quality, not just plumbing. Deterministic-assertion trap applies: stubbed summaries can always pass and cannot validate whether model decisions preserve key facts. MULTI-STEP: single generation judgment, so Agentic not Workflow. CANDIDATE-TEST-CHECK: (Agentic) feed fixed input with known key values to real summarizer; assert output preserves required facts via rubric/parser checks across repeated runs; catches hallucination/omission drift. (Integration alternative) stub summarizer returns canned correct text; verifies routing only and misses real misrepresentation failures. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow rejected because behavior text covers one summary step, not multiple agentic stages.","test_description":"Agentic evaluation test against the real summary model: provide representative datasets, score factual coverage of key metrics/issues/deploy outcomes, and fail when required facts are missing or contradicted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Any lower-level test with deterministic stubs cannot detect factual-faithfulness failures from real model output.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: this explicitly requires end-to-end delivery to an inbox, which depends on real network/email provider behavior. MOCK-HIDE: mocked mail transport can pass while SPF/auth, provider acceptance, or mailbox routing fails in reality. LLM-DEP: behavior is delivery success, not summary quality, so real model judgment is not required for this assertion. CANDIDATE-TEST-CHECK: (System) run full pipeline against test endpoints and a real test mailbox; assert message arrives with expected report artifact/subject; catches transport and config failures. (Integration alternative) mock SMTP/API client and assert send() called; misses real provider/inbox failures. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic rejected because behavior text is about inbox reachability, not evaluating model output correctness.","test_description":"System end-to-end test in a staging environment: execute one report run with live data-source endpoints (or staging equivalents) and live email delivery path to a test recipient inbox; assert receipt and basic report presence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Real inbox arrival cannot be proven at Integration level with mocked transport.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure spans delivery error handling, persistence, and subsequent-run retry orchestration. REAL-INFRA: local filesystem can be exercised in-process (temp dir) and delivery outage can be simulated by a failing mail client stub; no mandatory real external service needed for this behavior. INTEGRATION-BRAKE checks: (a) real OS/network/subprocess not strictly required for minimum failure mode; (b) no AI/ML output dependency; (c) no multi-agentic chain. CANDIDATE-TEST-CHECK: (Integration) run #1 with send client stub failing -> assert fallback file written; run #2 with send client succeeding -> assert prior report is retried and fallback state cleared; catches lost-persistence/no-retry bugs. (System alternative) use real unreachable email endpoint and scheduler process; catches infra-specific issues but exceeds minimum for stated behavior. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected because behavior text requires retry semantics, not real provider-specific outage characteristics.","test_description":"Integration test over orchestrator + persistence layer using a temp filesystem and controllable mail client stub across two sequential runs to validate save-on-failure and retry-on-next-run semantics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"This requires cross-module state handoff across runs, which Unit misses; real external infra is not necessary to catch the core failure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.35,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
